918&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td nowrap=nowrap valign=bottom style=text-align: left; padding-bottom: 4px; font-family: times new roman; font-size: 10pt;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In December 2010
 we entered into a membership interest purchase agreement (MIPA) with AF Bran Holdings-NL LLC and AF Bran Holdings LLC (Investors).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The transaction closed in January 2011.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Investors agreed to purchase units in Nutra SA for an aggregate purchase price of $7.7 million.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Prior to the transaction
 Nutra SA was&amp;#160;our wholly owned subsidiary.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Nutra SA owns 100% of Irgovel.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Initially after the closing
 effective in January 2011
 we owned a 64.4% interest in Nutra SA
 and the Investors owned a 35.6% interest in Nutra SA.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Parent Company received $4.0 million of the January 2011 proceeds.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The remaining $3.7 million
 less $0.5 million retained by Nutra SA for administrative expenses
 was invested in Irgovel for capital improvements and working capital needs.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We agreed to use $2.2 million of the funds received from the January 2011 transaction closing to repay amounts owed to the Class 6 general unsecured creditors in accordance with the Amended Plan.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The remaining $1.8 million was used for general corporate purposes
 other unsecured creditor claims and administrative expenses associated with the Chapter 11 Reorganization.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We received in 2011 an additional $3.9 million from the Investors - $1.9 million for the purchase of outstanding units in Nutra SA from us
 which was used by the Corporate and USA segments for working capital
 and $2.0 million for the purchase of new units in Nutra SA
 which were used by the Brazil segment to fund a capital expansion.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;These purchases increased the Investors' interest in Nutra SA to a 49.0% interest as of December 31
 2011.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In December 2012
 we received&amp;#160;an additional $1.5 million from the Investors for the purchase of new units in Nutra SA
 which were used by the Brazil segment to fund a capital expansion.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We made additional capital contributions valued at $1.5 million under the agreement
 consisting of the right to use certain proprietary equipment and forgiveness of fees Nutra SA owed us.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We must deliver and install the equipment at our expense
 within 90 days after requested by either the Investors or Irgovel.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Investors' interest remained 49.0% interest as of December 31
 2012.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;The Investors have the right to subsequently purchase from Nutra SA up to an additional 750
000 units for another $1
500
000.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If immediately prior to such purchase Nutra SA and Irgovel have sufficient cash to complete certain projects
 then the units will have no voting rights.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We determined that we continued to control Nutra SA
 after each of the membership interest sale transactions and&amp;#160;should continue to consolidate Nutra SA.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We treated each transaction similar to an equity transaction
 with no gain or loss recognized in consolidated net loss or comprehensive loss.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The $0.3 million historical cost of the equipment we contributed in December 2012
 is reflected in Nutra SA's balance sheet
 in the Brazil segment as of December 31
 2012.&amp;#160; The Investors' share of Nutra SA's net income (loss) increases (decreases) redeemable noncontrolling interest.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;Redeemable noncontrolling interest in Nutra SA is recorded in temporary equity
 above the equity section and after liabilities on our consolidated balance sheets
 because the Investors have the right to force a sale of Nutra SA assets in the future (see Drag Along Rights described below).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We have assessed the likelihood of the Investors exercising these rights as less than probable at December 31
 2012

 we&amp;#160;amended&amp;#160;the limited liability company agreement for Nutra SA (LLC agreement).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Pursuant to this amendment
 among other things
 any units held by the Investors after January 1
 2014
 accrue a yield at 4% if a certain milestone condition is satisfied
 and at 8% if the milestone condition is not satisfied (the Yield).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The milestone condition relates to Nutra SA having performed all of the following: obtaining additional back financing
 completion of the capital expansion project within certain spending limitations
 and operation of the plant post expansion at targeted processing levels&lt;font style=display: inline; font-size: 10pt;&gt;.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;Commencing with the first quarter of 2014
 Nutra SA must make distributions to the Investors quarterly in the amount equal to the previously accrued and unpaid Yield plus any additional distributions owed to the Investors.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Until March 31
 2014
 or if at any time Nutra SA is past due on its obligations to pay the Investors the Yield
 all amounts due to us for management fees or for shared employees as provided under the LLC Agreement shall be tolled and remain unpaid until all past due amounts
 if any
 owed to the Investors have been paid in full.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;Following the payment of the Yield
 Nutra SA must distribute all distributable cash (as defined in the LLC Agreement) to the members on March 31 of each year as follows: (i) first
 to the Investors in an amount equal to 2.3 times the Investors' capital contribution
 less the aggregate amount of distributions paid to the Investors
 (ii) second
 to us in an amount equal to (i) two times the capital contributions made by us
 less the aggregate amount of distributions paid to us; and (iii) third
 to us and the Investors in proportion to our respective membership interests.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;Under the LLC agreement
 the business of Nutra SA is to be conducted by the manager
 currently our CEO
 subject to the oversight of the management committee.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The management committee is comprised of three of our representatives and two Investor representatives.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Upon an event of default or a qualifying event
 we will no longer control the management committee and the management committee will include three Investor representatives and two of our representatives.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In addition
 following an event of default or a qualifying event
 a majority of the members of the management committee may replace the manager of Nutra SA.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;As of December 31
 2012
 there have been no events of default.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Events of default
 as defined in the MIPA

 defined as the occurrence
 in either 2012
 2013 or 2014
 of a 20% unfavorable variation in two out of three of the following: (i) revenue
 (ii) earnings before interest
 taxes
 depreciation and amortization (EBITDA) or (iii) debt

 which is defined as the failure to achieve 85% of planned EBITDA for three consecutive quarters

 which is defined as a material problem in a facility (unrelated to changes in law
 weather
 etc.) likely to cause a Nutra SA business plan deviation or Nutra SA EBITDA default
 which results in damages not at least 80% covered by insurance proceeds.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;As of December 31
 2012
 there have been no qualifying events.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The LLC agreement
 defines a qualifying event as any event prior to September 16
 2014
 which results
 or will result in
 (i) a person or group of persons exercising the right to appoint members to our board of directors holding one third or more of the votes of all board members
 (ii) the sale
 exchange
 pledge or use as guarantee of one half of our ownership interest in Nutra SA to a third party or (iii) the bankruptcy of RiceBran Technologies or Nutra SA.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;The Investors have certain rights

 bio-refining and marketing of numerous products derived from rice bran.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We have proprietary and patented intellectual property that allows us to convert rice bran
 one of the world's most underutilized food sources
 into a number of highly nutritious human food and animal nutrition products.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Our target markets are human food and animal nutrition manufacturers and retailers
 as well as natural food
 functional food and nutraceutical supplement manufacturers and retailers
 both domestically and internationally.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We have developed a bio-refining approach to processing raw rice bran into various value added constituents such as stabilized rice bran (SRB)
 rice bran oil (RBO)
 defatted rice bran (DRB) and a variety of other valuable derivative products from each of these core products.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We have three reportable business segments: (1) Corporate; (2) USA
 which manufactures and distributes SRB in various granulations along with other products derived from rice bran via proprietary and patented enzyme treatment processes; and (3) Brazil
 which extracts crude RBO and DRB from rice bran
 which are then further processed into a number of valuable human food and animal nutrition products.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Corporate segment includes selling
 general and administrative expenses including public company expenses
 litigation
 and other expenses not directly attributable to other segments.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;No Corporate allocations are made to the other segments.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;General corporate interest is not allocated.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;The USA segment consists of two locations in California and two locations in Louisiana all of which can produce SRB. One of the two Louisiana SRB facilities
 located in Lake Charles
 has been idle since May 2009.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The USA segment also includes our Dillon
 Montana Stage II facility which produces RiSolubles (a highly nutritious
 carbohydrate and lipid rich fraction of SRB)
 RiFiber (a fiber rich derivative of SRB) and RiBalance (a complete rice bran nutritional package derived from further processing SRB).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The manufacturing facilities included in our USA segment have proprietary and patented processing equipment and technology for the&amp;#160;&amp;#160;stabilization and further processing of rice bran into finished products.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In 2012
 approximately 50% of USA segment revenue was from sales of human food products and approximately 50% was from sales of animal nutrition products.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;The Brazil segment consists of the operation of our subsidiary Industria Riograndens De Oleos Vegetais Ltda. (Irgovel)
 located in Pelotas
 Brazil.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Irgovel manufactures RBO and DRB products for both the human and animal food markets in Brazil and internationally.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In refining RBO to an edible grade
 several co-products are obtained.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;One such product is distilled fatty acids
 a valuable raw material for the detergent industry.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;DRB is sold in bulk as animal feed and compounded with a number of other ingredients to produce complex animal nutrition products which are packaged and sold under Irgovel brands in the Brazilian market.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In 2012


  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  

  


 are discussed below.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block; margin-left: 0pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In May 2011
 the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) amended guidance on fair value measurement and expanded the required disclosures related to fair value.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The amendments
 among other things
 clarify that the highest and best use concept applies only to nonfinancial assets and addresses the appropriate premiums and discounts to consider in fair value measurement.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We adopted the guidance prospectively
 effective January 1
 2012.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Adoption did not have a significant impact on our financial position or results of operations.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In September 2011
 the FASB amended guidance on goodwill impairment testing.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The amendments permit us to first assess qualitative factors to determine whether it is more likely than not that the fair value of a reporting unit is less than its carrying amount as a basis for determining whether it is necessary to perform the two-step goodwill impairment test.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Previous guidance required us to test goodwill for impairment
 on at least an annual basis
 by comparing the fair value of a reporting unit with its carrying amount
 including goodwill (step one).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If the fair value of a reporting unit is less than its carrying amount
 then the second step of the test must be performed to measure the amount of the impairment loss
 if any.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Under the amendments
 we are not required to calculate the fair value of a reporting unit unless we determine that it is more likely than not that its fair value is less than its carrying amount.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We adopted the amendments effective for annual and interim goodwill impairment tests (if required) performed after January 1

 Louisiana facility was built at a cost of $3.8 million to process rice bran from a rice milling company adjacent to the facility.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The facility is built on leased land which is owned by the rice milling company.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The facility was idled in May 2009 due to lack of orders.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We recorded a $2.3 million impairment loss on the facility in 2009.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The facility is not classified as held for sale due to potential alternative uses and because we are not aggressively marketing the property.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We evaluated
 and continue to evaluate
 alternate uses of the facility.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Depreciation on the facility has continued after the facility was idled.&amp;#160; As of December 31
 2012
 the net book value of the idled facility included in property

 Baruch Halpern became a member of our board of directors.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Mr. Halpern is the principal in Halpern Capital
 Inc. (HC).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Under a February 2011 financial advisor agreement we are obligated to pay HC success fees ranging from 2.5% to 5.0% of the consideration received from certain equity
 convertible securities or debt transactions.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We must also issue warrants to purchase shares of common stock that equal from 2.5% to 5.0% of the consideration received in those transactions
 divided by either the market price of the common stock or the conversion price of the securities issued in the transaction.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;This agreement terminated April 1
 2012
 however
 we remain obligated to pay HC success fees and issue HC warrants on any transaction with an investor introduced by HC occurring though March 31
 2013.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman;  2009
 RiceBran Technologies (the Parent Company
 formerly known as NutraCea) filed a voluntary petition for relief under Chapter 11 of the United States Bankruptcy Code (Bankruptcy Code) in the United States Bankruptcy Court for the District of Arizona (the Bankruptcy Court)
 in the proceeding entitled In re:&amp;#160;&amp;#160;NutraCea
 Case No. 2:09-bk-28817-CGC (the Chapter 11 Reorganization).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;None of the Parent Company's subsidiaries
 including its Brazilian rice bran oil operation
 were included in the bankruptcy filing.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Parent Company continued to manage its assets and operate its business as debtor-in-possession under the jurisdiction of the Bankruptcy Court through the November 2010 plan effective date (see below).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Under the Bankruptcy Code
 certain claims against the Parent Company in existence prior to the filing of the bankruptcy petition were stayed during the pendency of the Chapter 11 Reorganization.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Additional claims arose subsequent to the filing date from the Parent Company's business operations
 its secured borrowing from Wells Fargo Bank
 N.A.
 its employment of professionals
 its disposition of certain non-core assets (as described below) and its treatment of certain executory contracts.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;On August 10
 2010
 the Parent Company and the Official Unsecured Creditors Committee filed with the Bankruptcy Court an amended plan of reorganization (Amended Plan) in accordance with the Bankruptcy Code.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Amended Plan called for the payment in full of all allowed claims.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Creditors voted overwhelmingly in favor of the Amended Plan and
 on October 27
 2010
 the Bankruptcy Court entered its order confirming the Amended Plan.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The confirmation order became final on November 10
 2010
 and the Amended Plan became effective on November 30
 2010.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;The liabilities subject to compromise became the Parent Company's payment obligations under the Amended Plan of approximately $7.0 million when the Amended Plan became effective.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;As of December 31 2011
 the portion of these obligations remaining unpaid was reflected as pre-petition liabilities in our consolidated balance sheets.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Interest accrued on the allowed liabilities subject to compromise from November 2009 through November 2010
 at an annual rate of 0.38%.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Interest accrued on the unpaid prepetition liabilities at an annual rate of 8.25% beginning in December 2010.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In January 2012
 we made our final $1.6 million distribution to the general unsecured creditors.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Cumulatively
 we made distributions totaling $7.0 million
 representing 100% of the amount owed under the Amended Plan
 plus accrued interest.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The distributions were made with the proceeds from (i) the sale of interests in Nutra SA LLC (Nutra SA) in 2011
 (ii) proceeds from the issuance of convertible notes

 there can be no assurances that our efforts will prove successful.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The accompanying consolidated financial statements do not include any adjustments that might be necessary if we are unable to continue as a going concern.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We took steps in 2012 and 2011 to improve profitability and liquidity by reducing our U.S. based employee headcount at both the corporate and plant operations level.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In the ongoing effort to improve profitability


 we issued shares of common stock and options to satisfy certain obligations in an effort to conserve cash.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In 2012 and 2011
 we also obtained funds from issuances of convertible debt and warrants.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We intend to obtain the necessary cash to continue our operations through the monetization of certain assets


  

  

  

  

  

  


  


  

  

  


 generally upon shipment for USA segment customers and Brazil segment international customers and upon customer receipt for Brazil segment domestic customers.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Each transaction is evaluated to determine if all of the following four criteria are met: (i) persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists; (ii) delivery has occurred; (iii) the selling price is fixed and determinable; and (iv) collectability is reasonably assured.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If any of the above criteria cannot be satisfied then such a transaction is not recorded as revenue
 or is recorded as deferred revenue and recognized only when the sales cycle is complete and payment is either received or becomes reasonably assured.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Changes in judgments and estimates regarding the application of the above mentioned four criteria might result in a change in the timing or amount of revenue recognized by such transactions.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We make provisions for estimated returns discounts
 and price adjustments when they are reasonably estimable.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Revenues on the statements of operations are net of provisions for estimated returns
 routine sales discounts
 volume allowances

000
000 shares of common stock were initially reserved for issuance under the 2010 Plan.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The amount reserved increases annually each January 1st by 5% of the outstanding shares as of the prior December 31st.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Additionally

000 increase in the number of shares of common stock reserved under the plan.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Under the terms of the 2010 Plan
 we may grant options to purchase common stock and shares of common stock to officers

 we issued options for the purchase of 1
217
889 shares of common stock in 2012
 at an exercise price of $0.14 per share.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The stock options vested in installments during 2012.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The $0.2 million grant date fair value of the options equaled the cash fees to which the directors were otherwise entitled.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In 2012
 our three executive officers agreed to accept stock options in lieu of receiving their full salary in cash.&amp;#160; Our three executive officers received cash equal to either 83.3% or 90.0% of their stated contract salary
 as detailed in their employment agreements
 and these officers were collectively issued stock options for the purchase of up to 852
592 shares of common stock at an exercise price equal to $0.12 per share.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The options vested in installments during 2012.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The $0.1 million grant date fair value of the options equaled the officers' salary forbearance.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In 2012
 we lowered the exercise price on outstanding options held by certain employees for the purchase of up to 21
717
441 shares of common stock to $0.08 per share from an average exercise price of $0.19 per share.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The stock price on the date of the re-pricing was $0.07 per share.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;No other terms of the options were modified.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We recorded expense of less than $0.1 million in 2012
 representing the difference between the fair value of the options before and after the modification.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Total unrecognized compensation increased less than $0.1 million as a result of the modification.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In 2011
 we entered into amendments to employment agreements with each of our four executive officers.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Twenty percent of each officer's salary for the last six months of 2011 was paid in stock options instead of in cash.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The options vested and became exercisable in installments during 2011.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Under the amendments we issued options to purchase 2
116
726 shares of common stock
 at an average exercise price of $0.20
 and an average initial term of 1.6 years.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In 2010
 we reached an agreement to settle all potential claims associated with the employment of Mr. Brad Edson
 our former chief executive officer.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The agreement was subject to the approval of the Bankruptcy Court and became effective upon court approval in 2011.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Mr. Edson agreed to return to NutraCea $0.4 million
 representing a bonus earned in 2008.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We recorded a receivable for the return of the bonus.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The corresponding income reduced selling
 general and administrative expenses in the first quarter of 2011.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;As partial payment of the receivable
 Mr. Edson forfeited 6
000
000 options granted in 2004 and returned 35
000 shares of common stock in payment of $0.3 million of his obligation.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The options had an exercise price of $0.30 per share and were outstanding and exercisable as of December 31
 2010.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We reduced the receivable from Mr. Edson
 reduced equity by $0.3 million
 and cancelled the options in 2011
 when the Bankruptcy Court approved the agreement.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The remaining $0.1 million receivable remains unpaid and reserved for due to uncertainty with regard to the collectability of the receivable as of December 31
 2012.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In 2011
 we reached an agreement to settle all potential claims associated with the employment of Mr. Todd Crow
 our former chief financial officer.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;As part of the settlement
 Mr. Crow was required to forfeit 1
662
942 options and return 9
666 shares of common stock held.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The agreement was subject to the approval of the Bankruptcy Court and became effective upon court approval in 2011.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We cancelled the stock and options in 2011.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The options had an average exercise price of $0.37 per share and were outstanding and exercisable as of December 31
 2010.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;No value was assigned to the cancelled stock or options because we transferred no cash or other assets in exchange.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In connection with the settlement

text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We have certain warrant agreements in effect for outstanding liability warrants that contain antidilution clauses.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Under the antidilution clauses
 in the event of equity issuances
 we may be required to lower the exercise price on liability warrants and increase the number of shares underlying liability warrants.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Equity issuances may include issuances of our common stock
 certain awards of options to employees
 and issuances of warrants and/or other convertible instruments below a certain exercise price.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;Common stock and warrant issuance to Buyer (Note 12)&lt;font style=display: inline; font-size: 10pt;&gt;
 c&lt;/font&gt;onvertible note and warrant issuances (Note 10)
 in 2012 and 2011 triggered the antidilution clauses in certain liability warrants and
 as a result
 we were required to lower the exercise price and increase the number of shares underlying certain liability warrants.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In addition

 reduced for estimated forfeitures
 and expensed on a straight-line basis over the requisite service period of the grant.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Forfeitures are estimated at the time of grant based on our historical forfeiture experience and are revised in subsequent periods if actual forfeitures differ from those estimates.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Black-Scholes-Merton option pricing model requires us to estimate key assumptions such as expected life
 volatility
 risk-free interest rates and dividend yield to determine the fair value of share-based awards
 based on both historical information and management's judgment regarding market factors and trends.&amp;#160; We treat options granted to employees of foreign subsidiaries as equity options.&amp;#160; We will use alternative valuation models if grants have characteristics that cannot be reasonably estimated using the Black-Scholes-Merton model.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We account for share-based compensation awards granted to non-employees and consultants by determining the fair value of the awards granted at either the fair value of the consideration received or the fair value of the equity instruments issued
 whichever is more reliably measured.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Generally we value options granted to non-employees and consultants using the Black-Scholes-Merton valuation model.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If the fair value of the equity instruments issued is used
 it is measured using the stock price and other measurement assumptions as of the earlier of (i) the date at which a commitment for performance by the counterparty to earn the equity instruments is reached or (ii) the date at which the counterparty's performance is complete.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The expense of stock awards issued to consultants or other third parties are recognized over the term of service.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In the event services are terminated early or we require no specific future performance



  


  


  


  


  


  


  


  

  


 U.S. Dollars.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The functional currency for Irgovel is the Brazilian Real.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Accordingly
 the balance sheet of Irgovel is translated into U.S. Dollars using the exchange rate in effect at the balance sheet date.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Revenues and expenses are translated using the average exchange rates in effect during the period.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Translation differences are recorded in accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) as foreign currency translation.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Gains or losses on transactions denominated in a currency other than the subsidiaries' functional currency which arise as a result of changes in foreign exchange rates are recorded as foreign exchange gain or loss in the statements of operations.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline; font-weight: bold;&gt;Cash and Cash Equivalents&lt;/font&gt; &amp;#8211; We consider all highly liquid investments purchased with an original maturity of three months or less at the time of purchase to be cash equivalents.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;As of December 31
 2012
 we maintain our cash
 including restricted cash
 and cash equivalents
 with major banks.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We maintain cash in bank accounts
 which at times may exceed federally insured limits.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We have not experienced any losses on such accounts.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline; font-weight: bold;&gt;Accounts Receivable and Allowance for Doubtful Accounts&lt;/font&gt; &amp;#8211; Accounts receivable represent amounts receivable on trade accounts.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The allowance for doubtful accounts is based on our assessment of the collectability of customer accounts and the aging of accounts receivable.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We analyze the aging of customer accounts
 customer concentrations
 customer credit-worthiness
 current economic trends and changes in our customer payment patterns when evaluating the adequacy of the allowance for doubtful accounts.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;From period to period
 differences in judgments or estimates utilized may result in material differences in the amount and timing of our provision for doubtful accounts.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We continue to evaluate our credit policy to ensure that the customers are worthy of terms and support our business plans.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline; font-weight: bold;&gt;Inventories - &lt;/font&gt;Inventories are stated at the lower of cost or market
 with cost determined by the first-in
 first-out method.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In the USA segment
 we employ a full absorption procedure using standard cost techniques.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The standards are customarily reviewed and adjusted annually so that they are materially consistent with actual purchase and production costs.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In the Brazil segment we use actual average purchase and production costs.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Provisions for potentially obsolete or slow moving inventory are made based upon our analysis of inventory levels
 historical obsolescence and future sales forecasts.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline; font-weight: bold;&gt;Long-Lived Assets
 Intangible Assets and Goodwill&lt;/font&gt; &amp;#8211; Long-lived assets
 consisting primarily of property
 intangible assets
 and goodwill
 comprise a significant portion of our total assets.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Property is stated at cost less accumulated depreciation.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Depreciation is computed on the straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Expenditures for maintenance and repairs are charged to operations as incurred while renewals and betterments are capitalized.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Gains or losses on the sale of property and equipment are reflected in the statements of operations.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Intangible assets are stated at cost less accumulated amortization.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;The carrying values of property and intangible assets with finite lives are evaluated periodically in relation to the expected future cash flows of the underlying assets and monitored for other potential triggering events that might indicate impairment.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Adjustments are made in the event that estimated undiscounted net cash flows estimated to be derived from the asset are less than the carrying value of the related asset.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The cash flow projections are based on historical experience
 management's view of growth rates within the industry
 and the anticipated future economic environment.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We are required to test goodwill for impairment at least annually (by policy December 31) and more often if an event occurs or circumstances change that more likely than not reduce the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying value.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In assessing the recoverability of goodwill
 we make estimates and assumptions about sales
 operating margin
 terminal growth rates and discount rates based on our budgets
 business plans
 economic projections
 anticipated future cash flows and marketplace data.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;There are inherent uncertainties related to these factors and management's judgment in applying these factors.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The fair value of a reporting unit has been determined using an income approach based on the present value of the future cash flows of each reporting unit.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The goodwill impairment test compares the fair value of individual reporting units to the carrying value of these reporting units.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If fair value is less than carrying value then goodwill impairment may be present.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The market value of our common stock is an indicator of fair value and a consideration in determining the fair value of our reporting units.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline; font-weight: bold;&gt;Revenue Recognition&lt;/font&gt; &amp;#8211; We recognize revenue for product sales when title and risk of loss pass to our customers
 generally upon shipment for USA segment customers and Brazil segment international customers and upon customer receipt for Brazil segment domestic customers.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Each transaction is evaluated to determine if all of the following four criteria are met: (i) persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists; (ii) delivery has occurred; (iii) the selling price is fixed and determinable; and (iv) collectability is reasonably assured.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If any of the above criteria cannot be satisfied then such a transaction is not recorded as revenue
 or is recorded as deferred revenue and recognized only when the sales cycle is complete and payment is either received or becomes reasonably assured.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Changes in judgments and estimates regarding the application of the above mentioned four criteria might result in a change in the timing or amount of revenue recognized by such transactions.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We make provisions for estimated returns discounts
 and price adjustments when they are reasonably estimable.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Revenues on the statements of operations are net of provisions for estimated returns
 routine sales discounts
 volume allowances

 we may be required to lower the conversion price on the convertible debt based on future issuances of our common stock
 awards of options to employees
 additional issuance of warrants and/or other convertible instruments below certain conversion prices.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We account for the conversion liabilities associated with these antidilution clauses as liability instruments
 separate from the host debt.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The conversion liabilities are classified as debt on our consolidated&amp;#160;&amp;#160;balance sheets.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;These conversion liabilities are valued using the lattice model each reporting period and the resultant change in fair value is recorded in the statements of operations in other income (expense).&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline; font-weight: bold;&gt;Derivative Warrant Liabilities &amp;#8211;&lt;/font&gt;&amp;#160;We have certain warrant agreements in effect that contain antidilution clauses.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Under these clauses
 we may be required to lower the exercise price on these warrants and issue additional warrants based on future issuances of our common stock
 awards of options to employees
 additional issuance of warrants and/or other convertible instruments below certain exercise prices.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We account for the warrants with these antidilution clauses as liability instruments.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;These warrants are valued using the lattice model each reporting period and the resultant change in fair value is recorded in the statements of operations in other income (expense).&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline; font-weight: bold;&gt;Share-Based Compensation &amp;#8211; &lt;/font&gt;Share-based compensation expense for employees is calculated at the grant date using the Black-Scholes-Merton valuation model based on awards ultimately expected to vest
 reduced for estimated forfeitures
 and expensed on a straight-line basis over the requisite service period of the grant.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Forfeitures are estimated at the time of grant based on our historical forfeiture experience and are revised in subsequent periods if actual forfeitures differ from those estimates.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The Black-Scholes-Merton option pricing model requires us to estimate key assumptions such as expected life
 volatility
 risk-free interest rates and dividend yield to determine the fair value of share-based awards
 based on both historical information and management's judgment regarding market factors and trends.&amp;#160; We treat options granted to employees of foreign subsidiaries as equity options.&amp;#160; We will use alternative valuation models if grants have characteristics that cannot be reasonably estimated using the Black-Scholes-Merton model.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We account for share-based compensation awards granted to non-employees and consultants by determining the fair value of the awards granted at either the fair value of the consideration received or the fair value of the equity instruments issued
 whichever is more reliably measured.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Generally we value options granted to non-employees and consultants using the Black-Scholes-Merton valuation model.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If the fair value of the equity instruments issued is used
 it is measured using the stock price and other measurement assumptions as of the earlier of (i) the date at which a commitment for performance by the counterparty to earn the equity instruments is reached or (ii) the date at which the counterparty's performance is complete.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The expense of stock awards issued to consultants or other third parties are recognized over the term of service.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In the event services are terminated early or we require no specific future performance

 when necessary
 to reduce that deferred tax asset if it is more likely than not that the related tax benefits will not be realized.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline; font-weight: bold;&gt;Use of Estimates&lt;/font&gt; &amp;#8211; The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Because of the uncertainty inherent in such estimates

 are discussed below.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block; margin-left: 0pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In May 2011
 the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) amended guidance on fair value measurement and expanded the required disclosures related to fair value.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The amendments
 among other things
 clarify that the highest and best use concept applies only to nonfinancial assets and addresses the appropriate premiums and discounts to consider in fair value measurement.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We adopted the guidance prospectively
 effective January 1
 2012.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Adoption did not have a significant impact on our financial position or results of operations.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In September 2011
 the FASB amended guidance on goodwill impairment testing.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The amendments permit us to first assess qualitative factors to determine whether it is more likely than not that the fair value of a reporting unit is less than its carrying amount as a basis for determining whether it is necessary to perform the two-step goodwill impairment test.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Previous guidance required us to test goodwill for impairment
 on at least an annual basis
 by comparing the fair value of a reporting unit with its carrying amount
 including goodwill (step one).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;If the fair value of a reporting unit is less than its carrying amount
 then the second step of the test must be performed to measure the amount of the impairment loss
 if any.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Under the amendments
 we are not required to calculate the fair value of a reporting unit unless we determine that it is more likely than not that its fair value is less than its carrying amount.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We adopted the amendments effective for annual and interim goodwill impairment tests (if required) performed after January 1

 we entered into a joint research and development agreement with a partner with the goal of developing technology to extract and concentrate protein from rice bran.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In March 2013
 the agreement was mutually terminated.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We each received (i) the right to separately develop
 modify and improve the jointly developed technology and (ii) nonexclusive
 nonroyalty-bearing license rights to separately exploit the technology.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We agreed to pay the partner a total of $1.3 million
 which is payable&amp;#160;in four equal quarterly installments beginning June 2013
 or
 alternatively
 $1.2 million as a lump sum in June 2013.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: left; font-family: 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: 10pt;&gt;In March 2013

 this January 2012 debenture was exchanged for a July 2012 debenture with a stated principal amount of $1.0 million
 representing the original principal amount plus interest which will accrue through the replacement debenture's January 2014 maturity.  In July 2012
 we also issued a new senior convertible debenture and related warrant and received $0.2 million in proceeds
 net of financing costs.  Each of the July 2012 debentures is convertible immediately at $0.07 per share.  Commencing February 2013
 we are required to redeem 1/12th of the $1.3 million combined principal each month until the January 2014 maturity date.  In lieu of a cash redemption we may elect to redeem the debentures by issuing a number of shares of common stock equal to the monthly redemption amount divided by the lesser of (i) the current debenture conversion price or (ii) 80% of the 20-day volume weighted average trading price of our common stock or (iii) the volume weighted average trading price of our common stock on the day immediately prior to the redemption date less $0.01.  The number of shares delivered may not exceed 20% of the number of shares traded in the 20-day trading period prior to payment.  The debentures are secured by a senior interest in substantially all of our assets
 excluding our interest in Nutra SA.  Pursuant to the terms of the debentures
 we may not pay any dividends while the debenture is outstanding.  Under the terms of the original January 2012 debenture

 we may be required to lower the conversion price on the convertible debt based on future issuances of our common stock
 awards of options to employees
 additional issuance of warrants and/or other convertible instruments below certain conversion prices.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We account for the conversion liabilities associated with these antidilution clauses as liability instruments

 Goodwill and Intangible Assets


 Intangible Assets and Goodwill&lt;/font&gt; &amp;#8211; Long-lived assets
 consisting primarily of property
 intangible assets
 and goodwill
 comprise a significant portion of our total assets.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Property is stated at cost less accumulated depreciation.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Depreciation is computed on the straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Expenditures for maintenance and repairs are charged to operations as incurred while renewals and betterments are capitalized.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Gains or losses on the sale of property and equipment are reflected in the statements of operations.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Intangible assets are stated at cost less accumulated amortization.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;The carrying values of property and intangible assets with finite lives are evaluated periodically in relation to the expected future cash flows of the underlying assets and monitored for other potential triggering events that might indicate impairment.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Adjustments are made in the event that estimated undiscounted net cash flows estimated to be derived from the asset are less than the carrying value of the related asset.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The cash flow projections are based on historical experience
 management's view of growth rates within the industry
 and the anticipated future economic environment.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We are required to test goodwill for impairment at least annually (by policy December 31) and more often if an event occurs or circumstances change that more likely than not reduce the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying value.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In assessing the recoverability of goodwill
 we make estimates and assumptions about sales
 operating margin
 terminal growth rates and discount rates based on our budgets
 business plans
 economic projections

 pursuant to a settlement agreement with a former customer
 we received $0.8 million in connection with a 2007 transaction with that customer.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We shipped products in 2007 to the customer and no revenue was recognized for the transaction under revenue recognition rules.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The customer had not remitted payment prior to the settlement.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The $0.8 million received is included in recoveries from former customers in the statements of operations for 2011.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;In 2007
 we closed on the sale of certain products to a customer.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The applicable criteria for revenue recognition were not met at that time.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The $1.0 million deposit we received in the transaction was carried as an other long-term liability on our balance sheet since 2007 until the fourth quarter of 2011
 when we eliminated the liability upon the resolution of certain legal matters associated with the transaction.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We recognized a reduction in operating expenses in the amount of $1.0 million



 Herbal Science Singapore Pte. Ltd. (HS) filed a proof of claim against the Parent Company in the amount of $1.5 million in the Chapter 11 Reorganization.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In November 2010
 we entered into a stipulated settlement agreement with HS and certain affiliates
 which was subsequently approved by the Bankruptcy Court.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The stipulation
 as amended
 provided that we would pay HS $0.9 million.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;During 2011
 we paid $0.4 million of our obligation to HS.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In the second quarter of 2011
 HS sold their receivable due from us to a third party (Buyer).&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In settlement of our remaining $0.5 million obligation to Buyer we issued to Buyer 2
576
775 shares of common stock and a warrant to purchase 605
730 shares
 at $0.23 per share
 expiring in November 2016
 in a noncash transaction.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The fair value of the common stock and warrant issued to Buyer exceeded our obligation to the Buyer by $0.2 million.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;This excess was recorded as a transaction cost in other expense in the second quarter of 2011.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The stock had a fair value
 based on the closing price of our stock
 of $0.6 million.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;The warrant had a fair value of $0.1 million
 determined using Black-Scholes valuation methodology.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;As a result of the settlement of our obligation to HS in 2011
 we became the sole member of Rice Rx
 LLC (RRX) and Rice Science
 LLC (RS)
 each Delaware limited liability companies formed with HS in December 2007.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Our ownership interest in RRX
 increased from 50% to 100% and our ownership interest in RS increased from 80% to 100%.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;In addition
 we were assigned all interests in the patentable pharmaceuticals
 SRB isolates and related intellectual property derived from the preliminary research and development activities of RRX and RS.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;The $0.9 million settlement was comprised of $0.6 million for the satisfaction of liabilities RRX and RS had payable to HS
 $0.1 million for interest expense on those liabilities
 $0.1 million for reimbursement of HS attorney fees
 and $0.1 million for the additional ownership interests in RRX and RS.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We used cash to satisfy our obligation to pay the $0.1 million for the ownership interests and $0.3 million of the liabilities to RRX and RS and settled the remainder of the liabilities
 interest and attorneys fees
 with issuance of the shares of common stock and the warrant to the Buyer.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We had a controlling interest in RS prior to the transaction
 therefore no gain or loss was recorded with the purchase of the additional RS ownership interests.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;We recorded the indicated loss
 representing the cash paid for the RS ownership interests and the noncontrolling interest derecognized with the transaction
 of $0.3 million in equity in 2011.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;RS had no loss from operations in 2012 or 2011.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-indent: 0pt; display: block;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=text-align: justify; text-indent: 0pt; display: block; font-family: Times New Roman; margin-left: 0pt; font-size: 10pt; margin-right: 0pt;&gt;We increased our interest in RRX from a noncontrolling interest to a controlling interest.&amp;#160;&amp;#160;Consequently
 in the second quarter of 2011
 we recorded a loss on the transaction
 equal to the cash paid for the RRX ownership interests and the net RRX liabilities assumed


  

  






















































 were terminated and cancelled in the first quarter of 2012
 when a subordinated convertible note was issued to the Halpern Entities

 a reconciliation of the beginning and ending balances
 separately presenting changes attributable to the following: (1) total gains or losses for the period (realized and unrealized)
 segregating those gains or losses included in earnings (or changes in net assets)
 and gains or losses recognized in other comprehensive income (loss) and a description of where those gains or losses included in earnings (or changes in net assets) are reported in the statement of income (or activities); (2) purchases
 sales
 issues
 and settlements (each type disclosed separately); and (3) transfers in and transfers out of Level 3 (for example
 transfers due to changes in the observability of significant inputs) by class of liability.
              
 -LegacyDoc This reference is SUPERSEDED by the Accounting Standards Codification effective for interim and annual periods ending after September 15
 2009.  This reference is included to help users transition from the previous accounting hierarchy and will be removed from future versions of this taxonomy.
              

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 including
 but not limited to: (a) expected term
 (b) expected volatility of the entity's shares
 (c) expected dividends
 (d) risk-free rate(s)
 and (e) discount for post-vesting restrictions.
              
                
              

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    





















    
  
      

In Millions
 unless otherwise specified

 are incurred on contractual obligations

 this January 2012 debenture was exchanged for a July 2012 debenture with a stated principal amount of $1.0 million
 representing the original principal amount plus interest which will accrue through the replacement debenture's January 2014 maturity.  In July 2012
 we also issued a new senior convertible debenture and related warrant and received $0.2 million in proceeds
 net of financing costs.  Each of the July 2012 debentures is convertible immediately at $0.07 per share.  Commencing February 2013
 we are required to redeem 1/12th of the $1.3 million combined principal each month until the January 2014 maturity date.  In lieu of a cash redemption we may elect to redeem the debentures by issuing a number of shares of common stock equal to the monthly redemption amount divided by the lesser of (i) the current debenture conversion price or (ii) 80% of the 20-day volume weighted average trading price of our common stock or (iii) the volume weighted average trading price of our common stock on the day immediately prior to the redemption date less $0.01.  The number of shares delivered may not exceed 20% of the number of shares traded in the 20-day trading period prior to payment.  The debentures are secured by a senior interest in substantially all of our assets
 excluding our interest in Nutra SA.  Pursuant to the terms of the debentures
 we may not pay any dividends while the debenture is outstanding.  Under the terms of the original January 2012 debenture
 we had been required to redeem 1/12th of the $0.9 million principal each month commencing August 2012 until the July 2013 maturity date.

 between total income tax expense or benefit as reported in the Income Statement for the year/accounting period and the expected income tax expense or benefit computed by applying the domestic federal statutory income tax rates to pretax income from continuing operations
 that is attributable to adjustments to capitalized costs deferred.
              
                
              

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 between total income tax expense or benefit as reported in the Income Statement for the year/accounting period and the expected income tax expense or benefit computed by applying the domestic federal statutory income tax rates to pretax income from continuing operations
 that is attributable to adjustments to U.S. net operating losses.
              
                
              

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 between total income tax expense or benefit as reported in the Income Statement for the year/accounting period and the expected income tax expense or benefit computed by applying the domestic federal statutory income tax rates to pretax income from continuing operations
 that is attributable to adjustments to expiration of US net operating losses.
              
                
              

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 or differences in the methodologies used to determine expense amounts for financial statements prepared in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles
 related to convertible debt issuance expenses.
              
                
              

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 between total income tax expense or benefit as reported in the Income Statement for the year/accounting period and the expected income tax expense or benefit computed by applying the domestic federal statutory income tax rates to pretax income from continuing operations

 expired or cancelled options.
